What an adventure it’s been this past MONTH! From multiple soccer tournaments, to a multiple day backpacking trip, mountain race, going back to work in a new role, taking airplanes for 24 hour media coverage, driving to multiple cities, and now capping it off with a retreat with someone I met through instagram… if you told me that this would happen, I would’ve called you crazy.

In retrospect, Working 7 days a week for an average of 14-18 hours has been a grind but totally worth it. Whether it’s going through footage, editing photos, recovering from races, or preparing a professional development for teacher’s in Anchorage, it’s been quite the ride. Tomorrow is going to be my first day off in I don’t know how long?😅 

Morale of the story: Don’t be hesitant to step out of your comfort zone and share your life and do something you love. You’ll never know what it might bring 🤷🏽‍♂️ @cotopaxi #SummerRewind #cotoadvocate #alaska #adventure #photography #videography #dream #soccer #sleddog #iditarod #hiking #youthsoccer

And that’s a wrap! What an end to the outdoor photography season 🏔️ 📸 Made many new friendships and explored parts of Alaska that I haven’t even touched before. I’m excited to say that next summer is being planned out as we speak and will be bigger than this one 👀 As for the details, I guess you’ll find out in the next few months or in 2024 🙌🏾

For this month’s Cotopaxi campaign, I’d like to share one way I like to share acts of kindness with the people I care about in my life. Photography and videography has always been something I love to do and something I don’t ever want to treat like a chore. So whenever I hang out with my close friends or go travel, I like to capture special moments in the form of a reel or pictures. What are some ways you choose to share random acts of kindness? #dogoodwithcotopaxi @cotopaxi

One habit that I’ve kept since I was 14 or 15 was getting up early. Not saying you have to get up at 4am, but having some kind of discipline goes a long way. The positives that I receive from getting up early include “me” time for doing whatever such as getting a workout in when everyone’s asleep, getting work done in my education and photography job, and prepping for whatever tasks I have for the day. Through this one habit, I’ve been able to have more family time in the evenings and be efficient as time goes on. What’s your one habit? #motivational #4am #workout #habits #alaska

You ever wondered about the forest by Girdwood on your way to Alyeska? Here’s the story:

“As the Seward Highway approaches Girdwood, travelers can see the remains of trees whose roots were swamped with salt water and killed during the 1964 Earthquake. Portage was devastated when much of the ground along Turnagain Arm sank five to nine feet. At high tide, the town that once lay at sea level was now under water. The ruins of buildings in the water are testament to that dramatic day the earth moved. Geologic evidence shows that four earlier earthquakes dropped the coastline here, just as the earthquake did in 1964. Past Girdwood, at an unmarked turnout, is evidence of another catastrophic seismic event in the area. A ghost forest older than the one that can be seen from the road rests partially buried in the silty banks of the Arm. It can only be seen at low tide by walking below the bank.”

-Alaska.org

“In winter, downhill and backcountry skiers, snowboarders, and cross-country skiers flock to Hatcher Pass. A fantastic network of cross-country ski trails is groomed around the Independence Mine area. Snowmobiling is also very popular west of the pass. Visitors are encouraged to check current snow and avalanche conditions before venturing into the backcountry. The Mat-Su Borough also maintains an excellent sledding hill near Independence Mine State Historical Park that is wildly popular with families and free to the public. The new Skeetawk Ski Area at the base of Hatcher Pass has 30 skiable acres of beginner downhill terrain.” 

-travelalaska.com
